# @cover src/os/kernel/loader/fs_exec_resolve.spl 30%
"""
# PATH exec-resolve hardening — empty-command fail-closed contract (Lane HARDEN-ROBUST)

Asserts the seed-verifiable fail-closed boundary of the sshd exec PATH resolver
(src/os/kernel/loader/fs_exec_resolve.spl): an empty argv[0] resolves to "" (the
caller treats "" as exit 127, "command not found") — never a crash and never a
silent default binary.

## Seed-execution scope (important)

`fs_exec_resolve` deliberately scans argv[0] via the freestanding-only raw byte
externs `rt_string_to_byte_array` / `rt_bytes_u8_at` (per the x64-freestanding
char_at bug, see the module docstring) and probes the filesystem via
`simpleos_fat32_stream_open`. None of those externs are registered in the seed
(`simple run`) interpreter, so every NON-empty input is not seed-executable —
the empty-command branch (which returns before touching any extern) is the only
path this in-process spec can drive.

The hostile-input properties for non-empty commands are bounded by construction
and cannot fault OOB:
  * the slash scan loops `while i < bytes.len().to_i64()` (no unchecked index);
  * a name containing '/' is returned verbatim for the caller/exec layer to
    validate (traversal is NOT this resolver's responsibility);
  * a bare name is probed as "<dir>/<name>" over a fixed 3-entry PATH list,
    first hit wins, otherwise "" (not-found).
Those branches are verified on the compiled kernel / QEMU path, not here.
"""

use std.spec
use os.kernel.loader.fs_exec_resolve.{fs_exec_resolve}

describe "fs_exec_resolve: empty-command fail-closed contract":
    it "an empty command resolves to empty (command-not-found, no default)":
        expect(fs_exec_resolve("")).to_equal("")

    it "resolving the empty command is stable (idempotent, no state leak)":
        expect(fs_exec_resolve("")).to_equal("")
        expect(fs_exec_resolve("")).to_equal("")
